I imagine these kind of anthros would fit well in settings like Mouse Guard where the animals, anthro and civilized or not, still retain the same proportions.

The basic premise could be that most of the smaller/weaker creatures like mice, rats, frogs and others would be capable of develope civilizations as their natural life spams is short compared to big predators.

In such scenarios a cat, which would be the equivalent of a dragon (just a quick example) for mice could outlive generations of mice without any change, but during all this time the mice would develop a civilization of their own and maybe at some point be able to slay the cat.

But by the same token the cat could be very wary about the mice plots and since the predators live for so long they also become more wise/cunning and deadly each year.

Just to toss some more ideas for the writers:
- Imagine villages of mices getting together to form a kingdom in order to slay the cat.
- Brave mice could form an expedition and travel to far lands seeking advice or alliance with other beings.
- In a river they could find the frog tribe which is terrorized by a snake.
- How could they help each other?

I hope this will give some ideas. :-)
